    "body": "### Problem\n\nI am trying to use on_lines to track edits to a file. When inserting or deleting a single line, I am getting multiple events rather that one, which messes up the line calculations of the logic.\n\nFor example, when inserting a new line with \"o\", I get the following two events:\n\n```\n{ {\n    firstline_0idx = 4,\n    lastline_0idx_excl = 4,\n    new_lastline_0idx_excl = 5\n  }, {\n    firstline_0idx = 4,\n    lastline_0idx_excl = 4,\n    new_lastline_0idx_excl = 5\n  } }\n```\n\nWhen deleting a line with \"dd\", I get the following events:\n```\n{ {\n    firstline_0idx = 4,\n    lastline_0idx_excl = 5,\n    new_lastline_0idx_excl = 4\n  }, {\n    firstline_0idx = 4,\n    lastline_0idx_excl = 5,\n    new_lastline_0idx_excl = 4\n  }, {\n    firstline_0idx = 4,\n    lastline_0idx_excl = 5,\n    new_lastline_0idx_excl = 4\n  } }\n```\n\nI am trying to roll these up into an \"edit range\" so I can see which lines have changed. Since I'm getting multiple events with different lastline/newline, this appears to represent multiple lines being created or deleted, instead of one.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n```lua\nfunction attach_to_buffer()\n  local bufnr = vim.api.nvim_get_current_buf()\n  local bufname = vim.api.nvim_buf_get_name(bufnr)\n  \n  print(\"Tracking edits for buffer \" .. bufnr .. \" (\" .. bufname .. \")\")\n  \n  vim.api.nvim_buf_attach(bufnr, false, {\n    on_lines = function(_, _, _, firstline_0idx, lastline_0idx_excl, new_lastline_0idx_excl)\n      -- Print the event immediately\n      local event = {\n        firstline_0idx = firstline_0idx,\n        lastline_0idx_excl = lastline_0idx_excl,\n        new_lastline_0idx_excl = new_lastline_0idx_excl\n      }\n      \n      print(\"on_lines event: \" .. vim.inspect(event))\n      \n      return false -- Keep attached\n    end\n  })\n  \n  print(\"Tracker attached. Edit the buffer to see events.\")\nend\n```\n\nThen either insert a line into a buffer via \"o\", or remove a line via \"dd\". You will see multiple events fire for each action.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\neither a single event fires, or if multiple events fire, then the combined difference between lastline / new_lastline is 1\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n10.4\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nNA\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nmacOs 14.6.1\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nghostty\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nghostty\n\n### Installation\n\nbrew",
